<section>
  <title>Convergence of Sequences</title>

<definition>
  <notation><m>\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} x_n=x_0</m></notation>
  <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n)</m> converges to a real number <m>x_0</m>if for every <m>\epsilon >0</m> there is an <m>N=N(\epsilon) \in \mathbb{N}</m> with the property that if <m>n &gt;N</m> then <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.</statement>
</definition>

<p>
  Approach to proving using the definition.
  <ol>
    <li>Start with goal ``<m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>'' and in scratchwork simplify <m>|x_n-x_0|</m> to see how its size depends on <m>n</m></li>
    <li>use what you got from simplifying <m>|x_n-x_0|</m> to solve the inequality ``<m>&lt;\epsilon</m>''</li>
    <li>your solution will suggest the ``<m>N(\epsilon)</m>'' in the definition of convergence</li>
    <li>start proof with ``Let <m>\epsilon >0</m>'' be given.  Then ``Choose <m>N=</m>'' whatever the ``<m>N(\epsilon)</m>'' is that you identified through your scratchwork</li>
    <li>Demonstrate ``<m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>'' using your scratchwork in reverse; you will have steps that include
    <ul>
      <li>``...because <m>n &gt; N</m>...''</li>
      <li>``...because <m>N=</m>'' your <m>N(\epsilon)</m></li>
      <li>if you use the ceiling function in your definition of <m>N(\epsilon)</m>, there will be a step where you drop it, citing ``<m>x \leq \lceil x \rceil</m>''</li>
      <li>this will be followed by lots of cancellations, probably, culminating in a ``<m>&lt; \epsilon''</m></li>
    </ul></li>
  </ol>
</p>

</section>


