<section>
  <title>Consequences of Convergence</title>
  
<definition>
  <notation><m>\lim_{n \rightarrow \infty} x_n=x_0</m></notation>
  <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n)</m> converges to a real number <m>x_0</m>if for every <m>\epsilon >0</m> there is an <m>N=N(\epsilon) \in \mathbb{N}</m> with the property that if <m>n &gt;N</m> then <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.</statement>
</definition>


<p>Take a moment to consider a consequence of ``... if n &gt; N, then <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.''</p>

<md>
  <mrow>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</mrow>
  <mrow>-\epsilon &lt; x_n-x_0 &lt; \epsilon</mrow>
  <mrow>x_0-\epsilon &lt; x_n &lt; x_0 + \epsilon </mrow>
</md>

<p workspace="3in"></p>

<p>The entire tail of the sequence lies in this interval.  (The sequence is eventually entirely in this interval.)</p>

<p>This interval around <m>x_0</m> is called an <term>epsilon neighborhood of <m>x_0</m></term>.</p>

</section>

<section>
  <title>Consequences of Convergence</title>
  <theorem>
    <statement>If <m>(x_n)</m> is a convergent sequence, then its limit is unique.</statement>
    <proof>
      <p>Suppose the limit is not unique.  Suppose there are two real nummbers <m>x_0</m> and <m>y_0</m> with <m>x_0 \neq y_0</m> for which <m>(x_n) \rightarrow x_0</m> and <m>(x_n) \rightarrow y_0</m>.</p>
      <p>Let <m>\epsilon = \frac{1}{2}|x_0-y_0|</m>.</p>
      <p>Since <m>(x_n) \rightarrow x_0</m>, there is an <m>N_x \in \mathbb{N}</m> for which <m>n &gt; N_x</m> implies <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.</p>
      <p>Since <m>(x_n) \rightarrow y_0</m>, there is an <m>N_y \in \mathbb{N}</m> for which <m>n &gt; N_y</m> implies <m>|x_n-y_0| &lt; \epsilon</m>.</p>
      <p>Choose <m>N=\max\{N_x, N_y\}</m>.  Then for <m>n &gt; N</m> we know
      <md>
        <mrow>|x_0 - y_0| \amp = |x_0 - x_n +x_n - y_0| </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp \leq |x_0 - x_n| + |x_n - y_0| \text{ by the triangle inequality }</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp &lt; \epsilon + \epsilon</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}|x_0-y_0| + \frac{1}{2}|x_0-y_0|</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = |x_0 - y_0|</mrow>
      </md>.  But this is absurd.  We cannot have <m>|x_0 - y_0| &lt; |x_0 - y_0|</m>.  Consequently, our supposition that the limit is not unique must have been incorrect.  Therefore,  the limit of a convergent sequence is unique.      
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>
</section>

<section>
  <title>Consequences of Convergence</title>

  <definition>
    <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n) \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>bounded above</term> if there is an <m>M \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>x_n \leq M</m> for all <m>n</m>.  A sequence <m>(x_n) \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>bounded below</term> if there is an <m>m \in \mathbb{R}</m> for which <m>m \leq x_n </m> for all <m>n</m>. A sequence <m>(x_n) \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>(totally) bounded</term> if is it bonded above and bounded below.</statement>
  </definition>

<p>This definition of bondedness agrees with the definition we made for bonded sets <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.</p>

  <definition>
    <statement>A sequence <m>(x_n) \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is <term>unbounded</term> if it is not totally bounded.  If we want more specificity, we can say a sequence with no upper bound is <term>not bounded above</term> and a sequence that does not hae a lower bound is <term>not bounded blow</term>.
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <example>
    <p workspace="3in">Give an example of a sequence that is bounded.  A sequence that is not bounded above.  A sequence that is not bounded below.</p>
  </example>

  </section>

<section>
  <title>Consequences of Convergence</title>

  <theorem>
    <statement>If <m>(x_n)</m> is a convergent sequence, then the sequence is totally bounded.</statement>
    <proof>
      <p>Suppose <m>(x_n) \rightarrow x_0</m>.  Choosing <m>\epsilon =1</m>, there is an <m>N \in mathbb{N}</m> for which <m>n &gt; N</m> means <m>|x_n-x_0| &lt; 1.</m>. This means <m>x_n &lt; L +1</m>.</p>
      <p>Let <m>M=\max\{|x_1|,|x_2|, \ldots,|x_{N-1}|,L+1\}</m>.  Then <m>(x_n) \subset [-M,M]</m>.  This shows that <m>(x_n)</m> is bonded above and below, so it is totally bounded.</p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>
</section>
